  "prompt": "How was the Alioth star named?",
  "response": "The name \"Alioth\" comes from an Arabic phrase meaning \"the primary of the herd\" or \"the herd.\" In historical contexts, it is associated with the Arabic word \"al-\u2018Aww\u0101\" (\u0627\u0644\u0639\u064e\u0648\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0621), which translates to \"the howler,\" referring to a group of stars in the Ursa Major constellation. Alioth is the brightest star in the Ursa Major constellation and is part of the Big Dipper asterism. \n\nThe name was adopted in Western astronomy through translations of Arabic texts in the medieval period, which often included star names derived from Arabic language and culture. Alioth's designation as Epsilon Ursae Majoris (\u03b5 Ursae Majoris) reflects its position in the constellation, where it is the fifth-brightest star in order of brightness.",
